    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{r^{2}-3r}{9-r^{2}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{r}{r+3}, r\ne 3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>If a polynomial is not in order, we order it by the variable<rsq/>s degrees.</p>
<p>If the leading coefficient is negative, we factor out <m>-1</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r^{2}-3r}{9-r^{2}}} \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}{{-r^{2}+9}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}{{-\left(r^{2}-9\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}{{-\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}} \\
                     \amp = {-\frac{r}{r+3}, r\ne 3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>r-3</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>r \ne 3</m>.</p>
</solution>
